# Create function to update 'date' field with formatted text
def date_to_text(df, date):
    # for loop to convert date from timestamp to string
    Date_text = []
    for x in df.index:
        Date_text.append(df[date][x].strftime('%b-%y'))
    df[date] = Date_text
    return df
In [3]:
# Create function to add missing values for Feb to Oct
def add_extended_date(dataframe):
    list_date = list(dataframe['Date']) # add a new date variable
    for x in ['02', '03', '04', '05', '06', '07', '08', '09', '10']:
        new_month = '2023-' + x + '-01T00'
        list_date.append(pd.Timestamp(new_month)) # add new months as timestamp data
    series_date = pd.Series(list_date, name='Date2') # add new months as categorical 
    df_date = series_date.to_frame()
    dataframe.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True) # reset index to perform concatenation
    df_new = pd.concat([dataframe, df_date], axis=1)
    return df_new

# Create function to create a sm graph
def create_sm_graph(df, df_params, index, filename):
    # Using categorical field "Date2" to create serial chart
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8.5, 11),
                           nrows=2,
                           layout='constrained')
    fig.suptitle('Appendix D')
    # Add x-axis and y-axis
    meter = df_params['Meter'][index]

    ax[0].bar(df['Date2'],
              df[str(meter)]/1000,
              width=0.8,
              color='dodgerblue',
              label="Irrigation")

    y_lower = df_params['y lower'][index]
    y_upper = df_params['y upper'][index]

    ax[0].set_ylim(y_lower, y_upper)
    #ax[0].set_yticks([0, 100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900])

    ax[0].spines['left'].set_linewidth(2)
    ax[0].spines['bottom'].set_linewidth(2)

    ax[0].set_xticks(['Oct-13', 'Oct-14', 'Oct-15', 'Oct-16', 'Oct-17',
                      'Oct-18', 'Oct-19', 'Oct-20', 'Oct-21', 'Oct-22',
                      'Oct-23'])

    ax[0].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)

    ax[0].set_xlim('Oct-13', 'Oct-23')

    graph_font = {'family': 'Arial',
                  'size':'x-large'}
    graph_font2 = {'family': 'Arial',
                   'size':'large'}

    # Set title and labels for axes
    vn = df_params['Probe'][index]
    loc = df_params['Location'][index]

    # Set title and labels for axes
    str_title = "2012-2022\nAverage Soil Moisture (" + vn + ")\n"\
                    "And Irrigation Meter " + str(meter) + " (" + loc + ")"
    ax[0].set_title(label=str_title.upper(),
                    **graph_font)
    ax[0].set_ylabel(ylabel="Gallons Applied\n(Thousands)",
                     color="dodgerblue",
                     **graph_font2)

    sns.set_style("white")
    plt.grid(axis='x')

    # twin object for two different y-axis on the sample plot
    ax2 = ax[0].twinx()
    # make a plot with different y-axis using second axis object
    ax2.plot(df["Date2"],
             df[vn],
             color="black",
             mfc="none",
             marker="s",
             label="Soil Moisture")

    ax2.set_ylabel(ylabel="Percent Soil Moisture by Volume",
                   color="black",
                   **graph_font2)

    ax2.set_ylim(5, 55)
    ax2.set_yticks([5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50, 55])

    # ask matplotlib for the plotted objects and their labels
    lines, labels = ax[0].get_legend_handles_labels()
    lines2, labels2 = ax2.get_legend_handles_labels()
    ax[0].legend(lines + lines2,
                 labels + labels2,
                 loc=2, #upper left
                 borderpad=.5,
                 ncol=2,
                 prop=graph_font2)

    # Produce the second chart or bottom half
    # Add x-axis and y-axis
    ax[1].bar(df['Date2'],
              df['Precipitation'],
              width=0.8,
              color='royalblue',
              label='Precipitation')

    ax[1].set_ylim(0, 14)
    #ax.margins(0)
    ax[1].spines['left'].set_linewidth(2)
    ax[1].spines['bottom'].set_linewidth(2)

    ax[1].set_xticks(['Oct-13', 'Oct-14', 'Oct-15', 'Oct-16', 'Oct-17',
               'Oct-18', 'Oct-19', 'Oct-20', 'Oct-21', 'Oct-22',
               'Oct-23'])
    ax[1].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)
    ax[1].set_xlim('Oct-13', 'Oct-23')

    graph_font = {'family': 'Arial',
                  'size':'x-large'}
    graph_font2 = {'family': 'Arial',
                   'size':'large'}

    # Set title and labels for axes
    str_title = "2012-2022\nAverage Soil Moisture (" + vn + ")\n"\
                "And Precipitation"
    ax[1].set_title(label=str_title.upper(),
                    **graph_font)
    ax[1].set_ylabel(ylabel="Precipitation (inches)",
                     color="royalblue",
                     **graph_font2)

    sns.set_style("white")
    plt.grid(axis='x')

    # twin object for two different y-axis on the sample plot
    ax2 = ax[1].twinx()
    # make a plot with different y-axis using second axis object
    ax2.plot(df["Date2"],
             df[vn],
             color="black",
             mfc="none",
             marker="s",
             label="Soil Moisture")

    ax2.set_ylabel(ylabel="Percent Soil Moisture by Volume",
                   color="black",
                   **graph_font2)

    ax2.set_ylim(5, 55)
    ax2.set_yticks([5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50, 55])

    # ask matplotlib for the plotted objects and their labels
    lines, labels = ax[1].get_legend_handles_labels()
    lines2, labels2 = ax2.get_legend_handles_labels()

    ax[1].legend(lines + lines2,
                 labels + labels2,
                 loc=2, #upper left
                 borderpad=.5,
                 ncol=2,
                 prop=graph_font2)

    plt.show()
    fig.savefig(filename, dpi=300)
